And hence we may gather how ad mans condition mut needs be in this lat age of his, in repect of his mind. The dieaes and ymptomes which do necearily arie from the darkning of thee Luminaries are thee which follow. Mentis imbecillitas, hebetudo, tupiditas, fatuitas; < in non-Latin alphabet > , (i.e.) tultitia, tarditas ingenii, judicii defectus;
< in non-Latin alphabet > , (i.e.) amentia, melancholia, deipientia, memoria imminuta, abolita. And thee proceed from the darkning of the everal and particular lights; there are others alo incident to age that hake all the powers of the heavens at once, and they are Vertigo, Carus, and Apoplexia. And thee are the mierable attendants of this
feeble tate, which is o much the more to be lamented, by how much the les it is to be helped. Sad are the infirmities before mentioned in any age, and mot difficultly do they receive their cure; but in this they admit of none at all. Some means may be by Phyicians ued for the proroguing of them, and keeping them off for a time; and for the mitigation of their violent aaults, but for the total preventing, or the abolute curing, let no man living hope for.

Foramuch as they are the only true, and proper Organs of eeing; however, it will be well worth our labour to conider, how the eyes may be called, the lookers out of the windows. One may be aid to look out of a window in a double ene, either when he looks through the glas of the window, and through the pellucidity of that mot refined body, dicerneth thoe things which are without; or when
he looks through the open Caement, or through ome open hole of the window, wherein there is nothing at all interpoeth between him and the object. Now in both thee enes may our interpretation well be made. For the Explication of it in the firt ene, we mut take notice of all thoe tranparent parts, through which the viible pecies mut of neceity pas before viion can be perfected: For as a man could ee nothing through a window, were it not made of glas, or of ome body alike Diaphanous: So neither could he perceive any thing with his eye, were not the parts thereof, through which paage is made, of the very ame nature. Now, the parts of the eye, through whoe bodies the viible pecies mut pas that they may be dicerned, are either the humours, or the Tunicles; The Humours are three, the watry, the Crystalline, and the glasie humour, o called by Anatomits; and you may perceive by their names that the ubtance of them all is Diaphanous; all which, howoever they wonderfully differ among themelves, and everal waies contribute to the ue and benefit of the eye, and conequently are made variouly intrumental unto viion, yet they all agree in this one thing, that they are tranparent;
and that they mut of neceity do, foramuch as into their bodies, and through their bodies, mut the viible pecies pas, before they can perfectly be dicerned by any man. And if one opacous, or darkome body interpoeth, they can go no further, but there they mut determine their coure.

HItherto Age hath been decribed unto us, as it hath influence upon all the functions and Faculties of a man; Superiour and Inferiour; Inward and Outward;
Animal, Vital, and Natural. And the Preacher hath exactly declared unto us, how far they are all weakned in this declining tate; he now in this Vere paeth to another head of Symptomes, which is uually called, Qualitates mutatae, taking notice of the imple affects, and thoe eminent and mot remarkable alterations that attend men in this condition. And here again he doth mot elegantly run over all the parts of man, and give only one mot ignificant alteration in each of them. The Compounding parts of man (as all men know, and as we have already heard) are the Soul and the Body. The principal affect of the mind in Age, is that of fear, which is hear expreed in repect of a double Object, a greater and a leer; which conequently makes the paion leer or greater; according to the encreae of Age; They hall be afraid of that which is high, and fears hall be in the way. The parts of the body are either inanimate, or animate; of the inanimate parts, the Hair receiveth the greatet alteration in Age, which is here ignified by thee words: The Almond tree hall flourih. The animate parts of the body, are alo of two orts, either the hard, and cruty parts, or the oft and pongy parts; and thee two are uually
known by the names of the Spermatical and Sanguineous parts. The change of the former of thee in age, is intimated unto us, in thoe words, The Grahopper hall be a burden; the change of the latter in thoe, Deire hall fail; as it followeth more clearly hereafter. After this mot myterious and Hieroglyphical decription of the Symptomes of Age, he doth in a plain and eaie tranition pas from thoe general Symptomes that attend a man all along this tate of weaknes, unto thoe particular ones, that do more immediatly forerun his diolution: For man goeth to his long home, and the mourners go about the treets.

