The econd ignification of the word is avum, eculum an age, a certain long pace of time, that is, commenurate with the duration of the thing, that is poken of A perpetuity (as I may o ay) that is circumcribed; an everlatingnes that lats as long, as the thing of which it is affirmed: It is aid of an Hebrew Servants refuing to go out free,Deut. 15. 17. Exod. 21. 6. His Master hall bore his Ear through with an Aul, and he hall erve him for ever. And again when Hannah reolved to preent her on Samuel to the Lord, he aith, I will bring him, that he may appear before the Lord, and there abide for ever: 1 Sam. 1. 22. 28. which Term for ever is afterwards explained, when he doth bring him and preent him; then he aith, I have lent him to the Lord as long as he liveth: 1 Sam. 27. ult.
Now in this ene alo may the word be taken in this place, o long as Death lives (and it is the lat enemy that hall be detroyed) it will keep in its poeion, all that it hath, or hall urprize: The Graves mut be our homes, when once we come there, as long as there is any Dut to cover us, or Heavens to urround us. Men lieth down and rieth not, till the Heavens be no more, they hall not awake, nor be raied out of their leep. Job. 14: 12. Untill the grave hall not onely ceae from craving, but from being;
and untill death be wholly wallowed up of victory, all thoe Bodies that are under their power, mut there quietly remain, as in their own unalterable habitations.

It remains now, that I only name unto you that Symptome of Old Age, at the time of death; that is here ignified unto us, by the Wheel broken at the Citern;
which cannot but be undertood, to be the ceaing of the Pule; the Intruments of Pulation decay, and can no longer perform that work, which mut necearily be continued for the preervation of life;Exod. 14. 24, 25. It came to pas when the Lord had a purpoe immediately to detroy the Hot of the Aegyptians, that he looked upon them, and troubled them, and took off their Charet wheels, that they drave heavily. Whenoever it is the good pleaure of God to give that word of Command, that the Tabernacle of our bodies, hould be as they were; his purpoe is eaily dicerned before-hand by his looking upon us, and troubling us, and giving diturbance unto, and taking off, thoe Charet wheels, upon which our life is turned; but yet this is far more apparent in the time of Age, for then the Charet wheels are more enibly hindered and removed, and o taken off by degrees. The old mans Pule doth yearly and dayly decline, both in repect of the mover, the troke and the intervall; o that it mut needs beat more languidly, lower, and eldomer than it did before. The Faculty grows weaker, the ue is not o urgent, nor the Intruments o vigorous, in age, wherefore all the Caues of a quick and a lively Pule failing, the ad effect thereof
mut undoubtedly follow; nor will it ever ceae declining, till it ceaeth beating, and then the man immediately ceaeth living; Pulus, rarus, tardus, languidus & nonnunquam intermittens, is the true pule of the old man, all the while he is in that condition, and is like unto the toling of a paing-bell, which may put him and all his friends in mind, that he is hortly going the way of all fleh, but Pulus omnino abolitus ive aphyxia, (which is the Symptome here mentioned,) is the condition of the dying man, and is like the tinting of the Paing-bell, or rather the ringing out of the Knell, which gives notice unto all that he is gone, and may erve as a loud, and ditinct invitation to the Funeral.

Now, as this part of Phyick needs it mot, o I am as bold to ay, it is as capable of improvement as any other part whatoever; And the improvement that may be made thereof would be as ueful to Mankind as any one dicovery of Nature, that hath at any time hitherto been made. Let none give over their Patients when they come to be burdened with the infirmities of Age, as though they were altogether uncapable of having any good done unto them;
for, as this will argue great weaknes and ignorance in the Phyician, o it is exceeding curelty to the Patient; For, as the lothful in his work is brother to a great water; o thoe that are negligent towards their ancient Friends, are very neer of kin to thoe inhumane Barbarians and Americans, who with great pomp and alacrity, both kill and devour them; thinking thereby they perform a mot charitable office, in delivering them from thoe incurable maladies, which will for ever render them mierable: But ure an indutrious Artit may find out wayes to be charitable at a more merciful rate. The Methods which are already known to ome more quickighted herein then their fellowes, do abundantly teach us, that although a perfect cure is not to be propoed or hoped for; yet a conervative cure in repect of Age, and, a compleat Cure in repect of ome of the dieaes before mentioned, and a palliative in repect of mot of them, may eaily be effected. A convenient Diet, and meet Applications of proper Medicines (uppoed alwayes, the bleing of God thereupon) cannot but preerve old Men, and hinder and keep off thoe Mieries which otherwie would ooner creep upon them, and give much eae, and very coniderable
rebukes, to the violent aaults of all thoe, that have already taken poeion: But thoe things which are already known by the mot knowing Men in the World, are little or nothing in comparion of thoe that remain yet to be known upon this Subject. The high and upreame matters thereof being yet unattempted by any, cannot but tir up more edulous and active Phyicians to be aiming at leat at the attaining them; wherein if they hall not poibly accomplih to their full atisfaction their intended purpoe, yet urely they will much out-doe all thoe who content themelves with Projects of a lower Sphear.
